    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-22T06:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-22T06:30:00-05:00" n="29"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d29">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">756.94/113: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Batavia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dickover</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Batavia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-22T19:00:00+07:30"
                            >May 22, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 22—5:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>There has been a certain reluctance lately among the local officials to give this
                    office information about stocks, etc., of export commodities <pb facs="0030"
                        n="22" xml:id="pg_22"/> especially tin and cinchona bark. Today this
                    Consulate General learned from a responsible official that this reluctance is
                    due to fear that the United States will buy up so much of the stocks on hand
                    that Japan, which is insisting upon its economic dependence upon the Dutch East
                    Indies, will be given real cause for alarm and possible action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dickover</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
